{"term":"1967","caseName":"Reading Company v. Brown","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1967/127","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 05, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/14920","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Francis Shunk Brown, 3d, etc.","start":0,"stop":22.074,"duration":22.07},{"text":"Mr. Rhoads?","start":22.074,"stop":23.573,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":23.573,"stop":26.151,"duration":2.58},{"text":"I would like, if I may, to enter two questions which were asked by Mr. White yesterday, by members of the court.","start":26.151,"stop":33.252,"duration":7.1},{"text":"Mr. Justice Black asked how the fire started.","start":33.252,"stop":37.539,"duration":4.29},{"text":"On the record, this is a fire of undetermined origin.","start":37.539,"stop":41.798,"duration":4.26},{"text":"For the purposes of this argument we of course have admitted negligence of the receiver but it's a fire of undetermined origin.","start":41.798,"stop":50.914,"duration":9.12},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, you asked whether and about the availability of the bond.","start":50.914,"stop":55.858,"duration":4.94},{"text":"The bond is a performance bond.","start":55.858,"stop":57.457,"duration":1.6},{"text":"It is available, of course.","start":57.457,"stop":59.231,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Its amount doesn't meet the enormous claims here.","start":59.231,"stop":66.268,"duration":7.04},{"text":"This matter would be here no matter what the amount, I believe, because we feel so strongly that this claim, an unliquidated claim for property damages, arising from a negligence a receiver during a Chapter XI proceeding is not entitled to the first status priority which claimants seek.","start":66.268,"stop":93.794,"duration":27.53},{"text":"As Your Honors have said in recent cases, very recent cases, where a priority is sought, the burden on the claimant is a very heavy one.","start":93.794,"stop":109.992,"duration":16.2},{"text":"And may I quote Your Honor's words in the case of Nathanson against the National Labor Relations Board in which this Court said the theme of the Bankruptcy Act is equality of distribution.","start":109.992,"stop":122.832,"duration":12.84},{"text":"And if one claimant is to be preferred over others, the purpose should be clear from the statute.","start":122.832,"stop":130.405,"duration":7.57},{"text":"We submit that there's no such clarity here.","start":130.405,"stop":134.197,"duration":3.79},{"text":"The Act is unim -- is unambiguous.","start":134.197,"stop":139.218,"duration":5.02},{"text":"If claimant is to succeed, he must concisely and convincingly bring the claim within Section 64, subsection (a) (1) of the Act.","start":139.218,"stop":153.994,"duration":14.78},{"text":"That Act provides that cost and expenses of administration, including the actual and necessary cost and expenses of preserving the estate subsequent to the filing of the petition, are entitled a first priority.","start":153.994,"stop":174.59,"duration":20.6}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why isn't the operation of a business by the receiver in order to carry on the business for the purpose of preserving and as far as possible?","start":174.59,"stop":189.398,"duration":14.81},{"text":"Why are not the expenses of that carrying on?","start":189.398,"stop":193.008,"duration":3.61},{"text":"What are the administrative expenses?","start":193.008,"stop":195.378,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"The expenses of carrying on that business, Your Honor, most certainly are cost and expenses of administration, provided they are necessary and this necessary is based on the definition and narrow wording of the statute and there can be no question.","start":195.378,"stop":217.585,"duration":22.21},{"text":"If the costs are necessary such as are closely and approximately related to the carrying on the business, costs which can be reasonably anticipated.","start":217.585,"stop":232.729,"duration":15.14},{"text":"They are cost of administrations entitled of first priority.","start":232.729,"stop":235.698,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they were operating a railroad and the Indians had threw sparks out during the operation, would that be a part of the administrative expenses?","start":235.698,"stop":245.088,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor pleases, that would be dealt with under Section 77 on the railroad reorganization sections which in -- which codify the equitable principle.","start":245.088,"stop":258.298,"duration":13.21},{"text":"They are not applicable to either Chapter XI or the liquidating bankruptcy proceedings.","start":258.298,"stop":266.36,"duration":8.06},{"text":"Congress has of -- has provided for a different set of rules applicable to situations involving railroads as the Acts so clearly shows in Section 77 (n).","start":266.36,"stop":277.537,"duration":11.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it's necessary to carry on the business, why can you -- how can you say it's not necessary?","start":277.537,"stop":285.321,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"If it's necessary to carry on the business, Your Honor, it is a cost and expense of administration.","start":285.321,"stop":291.567,"duration":6.25},{"text":"But there is nothing necessary about negligence in the use of the word --","start":291.567,"stop":296.471,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I never said that was negligence but there is something necessary about carrying on the business out of which the negligence come?","start":296.471,"stop":303.352,"duration":6.88}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor please, I don't think there can be any question that the cost of repairs, cost which go directly to either developing, preserving or liquidating in a estate are cost and -- as an expense of administration.","start":303.352,"stop":325.989,"duration":22.64},{"text":"But uncontemplated, negligent results -- expenses, which result from such things cannot be considered necessary.","start":325.989,"stop":337.809,"duration":11.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why can't -- why do you --","start":337.809,"stop":338.341,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Necessity and negligence are emphatetical in the language.","start":338.341,"stop":346.33,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why do you not have to contemplate that in the operation of the business of this kind, it might be negligence?","start":346.33,"stop":355.268,"duration":8.94},{"text":"Why is it not just --","start":355.268,"stop":357.328,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would be perfectly reasonable therefore.","start":357.328,"stop":360.799,"duration":3.47},{"text":"And I think that practice will show that the payment of the insurance premium such as to establish the estate here are reasonable cost and necessary cost.","start":360.799,"stop":378.333,"duration":17.53},{"text":"This is, they contemplate the carrying on of a business.","start":378.333,"stop":383.331,"duration":5},{"text":"It's the reasonableness not the failure to act as a reasonable man which comes into this definition of actual and necessary.","start":383.331,"stop":392.957,"duration":9.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I was asking you this question, not to indicate any --","start":392.957,"stop":395.939,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I appreciate that.","start":395.939,"stop":396.634,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of any conclusion but to rather challenge your idea that this is unambiguous as you say it is.","start":396.634,"stop":403.633,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"To me the Act is unambiguous because you must read Section 64 subsection (a) (1) in the light of the definition section and it is cost and expenses of administration are defined in this Act.","start":403.633,"stop":421.059,"duration":17.43}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Government in its brief, as I read it, seems to concede that some torts might be cost of administration.","start":421.059,"stop":433.521,"duration":12.46},{"text":"In your answer to Justice Black, did I detect to your agreement with that and otherwise let's assume that this is not a railroad which is covered by different statute but a dry cleaning establishment and one of its trucks doing a Chapter XI interval, one of its trucks delivering clean clothes to the customers that negligently struck somebody.","start":433.521,"stop":461.486,"duration":27.96},{"text":"Would that be -- would that kind of a tort be in your view under the --","start":461.486,"stop":466.05,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Stewart, I think this is a very interesting -- intellectual -- my point of view, under the Act expressly worded, it would not be.","start":466.05,"stop":475.037,"duration":8.99}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It would not be.","start":475.037,"stop":475.217,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I think a more strict view of the Act than the Government does.","start":475.217,"stop":480.814,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":480.814,"stop":481.038,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that it is possible that --","start":481.038,"stop":482.973,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Or a customer coming in to the store and --","start":482.973,"stop":485.367,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"And tripping -- coming in your dry cleaning establishment --","start":485.367,"stop":488.219,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":488.219,"stop":489.075,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- coming in and tripping --","start":489.075,"stop":490.008,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":490.008,"stop":490.597,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for the purpose of preserving continuing developing aspect?","start":490.597,"stop":493.922,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":493.922,"stop":494.116,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"This is very interesting.","start":494.116,"stop":495.016,"duration":0.9},{"text":"This is very close.","start":495.016,"stop":496.179,"duration":1.16},{"text":"I disagree on the Act as it a -- as it pre -- readilly --","start":496.179,"stop":498.693,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think no tort --","start":498.693,"stop":499.098,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I think this should be for Congress.","start":499.098,"stop":501.198,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think no claims and negligence of any kind?","start":501.198,"stop":503.977,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"No claim.","start":503.977,"stop":504.237,"duration":0.26},{"text":"My position is a very strict one and it would be that no claim.","start":504.237,"stop":508.671,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But that would go this far than Mr. Rhoads.","start":508.671,"stop":511.005,"duration":2.33},{"text":"I gather Knight really leased, didn't they?","start":511.005,"stop":513.717,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Knight really leased -- it was an industrial building of 8-storey --","start":513.717,"stop":516.982,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I suppose under the lease arrangement, as I take it usually happens.","start":516.982,"stop":521.462,"duration":4.48},{"text":"There are certain repairs which are the responsibility of the receiver.","start":521.462,"stop":525.832,"duration":4.37},{"text":"I suppose it was a pipe and it needed a welding job or something and then an employ --","start":525.832,"stop":530.273,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"A cost of repair?","start":530.273,"stop":531.447,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes -- no.","start":531.447,"stop":531.984,"duration":0.54},{"text":"I suppose it's an employee of the receiver, on the maintenance crew --","start":531.984,"stop":537.534,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":537.534,"stop":537.985,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- who went to the leased premises using a blowtorch negligently, he caused this fire.","start":537.985,"stop":545.084,"duration":7.1},{"text":"Even then, you'd say this is was not --","start":545.084,"stop":547.525,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that this is not a cost and expense of administration as --","start":547.525,"stop":553.189,"duration":5.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the only thing that would be --","start":553.189,"stop":553.831,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as provided for in the Act.","start":553.831,"stop":555.627,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The only thing that would be I gather is the cost of the material that the employee had to use and his wages and that sort of things, is that it?","start":555.627,"stop":562.612,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"The necessary expenses.","start":562.612,"stop":565.052,"duration":2.44},{"text":"You cannot read this Act.","start":565.052,"stop":567.733,"duration":2.68},{"text":"The administrative expenses cannot be read separate from the word “necessary”.","start":567.733,"stop":574.06,"duration":6.33},{"text":"In 64(a) (1), you have the words “Cost and expenses of administration”, including the “Actual and necessary cost” preserving the estate subsequent to filing the petition.","start":574.06,"stop":585.929,"duration":11.87},{"text":"Now, obviously, these are not, this claim is not within the “including the actual and necessary cost of filing subsequent to the petition.”","start":585.929,"stop":595.701,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Although, certainly in my hypothetical.","start":595.701,"stop":597.805,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"It --","start":597.805,"stop":597.936,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The repair was necessary to the operation of the business of leasing the premises.","start":597.936,"stop":601.701,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"No question of the cost of that would be an expense.","start":601.701,"stop":605.012,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What would you say if this is not Chapter X?","start":605.012,"stop":609.595,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because again you're --","start":609.595,"stop":611.321,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, what?","start":611.321,"stop":612.082,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it would -- if -- I mean it might well have been but we are not concerned with a Chapter X proceeding here because -- that you have a different set of rules, a greater adoption or adaptation into the procedures provided by Congress of looser roles.","start":612.082,"stop":633.385,"duration":21.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I am right (Inaudible) that Section 64 which says, it's applicable to Chapter XI?","start":633.385,"stop":641.71,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":641.71,"stop":643.028,"duration":1.32},{"text":"They -- there are specific sections of the Act which incorporate all of the liquidating bankruptcy provisions in the Chapter XI proceedings and say that Chapter XI proceedings are governed by that section of the procedures as established by the Act and by no others --","start":643.028,"stop":659.951,"duration":16.92}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But the provision that says 64 is applicable says that insofar as consistent with -- and insofar is not inconsistent with this chapter.","start":659.951,"stop":669.679,"duration":9.73}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"With Chapter XI.","start":669.679,"stop":670.916,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":670.916,"stop":671.386,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":671.386,"stop":672.941,"duration":1.56},{"text":"And there is nothing inconsistent in the --","start":672.941,"stop":677.144,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's a --","start":677.144,"stop":677.522,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"It's correct.","start":677.522,"stop":678.457,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- difference between the aims of Chapter XI and the aims of bankruptcy.","start":678.457,"stop":684.279,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"In a very --","start":684.279,"stop":685.677,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you must -- there's nothing that -- there's no way to rehabilitate anything straight bankruptcy and there certainly is in Chapter XI.","start":685.677,"stop":694.184,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but the preservation --","start":694.184,"stop":696.956,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And the -- and normally you don't --","start":696.956,"stop":697.24,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- elements of both are the same.","start":697.24,"stop":700.034,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh yes, but normally you don't continue a business and with -- and you don't run a business in bankruptcy.","start":700.034,"stop":705.053,"duration":5.02},{"text":"You liquidate a business.","start":705.053,"stop":706.965,"duration":1.91},{"text":"You -- and in XI, the whole idea is to keep the business going and use this -- the debtor in possession.","start":706.965,"stop":713.499,"duration":6.53},{"text":"And the -- so the whole object is to continue the business and to operate it.","start":713.499,"stop":720.667,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":720.667,"stop":721.499,"duration":0.83},{"text":"At times it is the debtor --","start":721.499,"stop":722.585,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"At times --","start":722.585,"stop":722.609,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- who's in possession --","start":722.609,"stop":723.106,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it always is in XI.","start":723.106,"stop":725.125,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not -- it was not so in this case.","start":725.125,"stop":727.645,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But during the XI proceeding?","start":727.645,"stop":728.661,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":728.661,"stop":730.223,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, --","start":730.223,"stop":730.306,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"To read the --","start":730.306,"stop":730.773,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you say the --","start":730.773,"stop":731.191,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"The receiver is the trust -- that the trustee here was the receiver.","start":731.191,"stop":734.649,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you get a petition under Chapter XI approved?","start":734.649,"stop":738.135,"duration":3.49},{"text":"I mean, you have to allege -- that makes some allegations, don't you, that you want to extend and pay off some of your debts --","start":738.135,"stop":742.818,"duration":4.68}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":742.818,"stop":744.858,"duration":2.04},{"text":"And it is a -- it is -- your Chapter XI is a rehabilitation proceeding but --","start":744.858,"stop":749.042,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I said.","start":749.042,"stop":749.579,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it is -- but it is not always the debtor in possession.","start":749.579,"stop":753.002,"duration":3.42},{"text":"It is a --","start":753.002,"stop":753.169,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I agree, not always, no, I agree with that.","start":753.169,"stop":755.541,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I'm sorry, I misunderstood Your Honor.","start":755.541,"stop":756.997,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I agree not always but there were -- certainly, there was a receiver here, a trustee here.","start":756.997,"stop":762.738,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":762.738,"stop":763.548,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":763.548,"stop":763.94,"duration":0.39},{"text":"But the aim was to rehabilitate this but --","start":763.94,"stop":765.786,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"The aim was to rehabilitate --","start":765.786,"stop":767.184,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and operate the business.","start":767.184,"stop":768.499,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and to operate the business just as in liquidating bankruptcies quite often there's a period of considerable length of operating the business and attempt to preserve and to secure the maximum equitable distribution upon general creditors of the greatest asset possible.","start":768.499,"stop":784.018,"duration":15.52}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the Reading Company have any remedy here for the injury suffered?","start":784.018,"stop":788.428,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"The Reading Company has -- I submit, Your Honor, two remedies.","start":788.428,"stop":794.315,"duration":5.89},{"text":"The bond, as suggested by Mr. Chief Justice which is of course in amount is inadequate.","start":794.315,"stop":798.685,"duration":4.37},{"text":"It also has --","start":798.685,"stop":799.746,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Does this bond cover tort --","start":799.746,"stop":802.468,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's a --","start":802.468,"stop":802.873,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- its in the receiver or?","start":802.873,"stop":804.118,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think there's any question.","start":804.118,"stop":805.494,"duration":1.38},{"text":"It's a performance bond.","start":805.494,"stop":807.409,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Now it may be that courts shouldn't require larger bonds than they had.","start":807.409,"stop":811.53,"duration":4.12},{"text":"But it's a performance bond --","start":811.53,"stop":811.744,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But if -- just a moment on that.","start":811.744,"stop":814.119,"duration":2.38},{"text":"Is it a performance bond for the benefit of third parties?","start":814.119,"stop":819.34,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"I would -- Your Honor, I must say I have not read the terms of that bond carefully not to say with certainty.","start":819.34,"stop":826.39,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if this is a -- this is not --","start":826.39,"stop":826.913,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"But I assume it is.","start":826.913,"stop":828.194,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If this is not part of the administration, how does the court -- perform bond reach it?","start":828.194,"stop":833.831,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no question, this is part of the administration but it's not every cost and expense in the administration which is entitled to the first priority.","start":833.831,"stop":841.259,"duration":7.43}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the other remedy?","start":841.259,"stop":842.516,"duration":1.26},{"text":"You said they're --","start":842.516,"stop":842.885,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"The plenary suit.","start":842.885,"stop":844.234,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Against who?","start":844.234,"stop":844.496,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. White, my opponent already has a plenary suit, which is referred to in one of my --","start":844.496,"stop":848.582,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Against whom?","start":848.582,"stop":849.201,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- witness.","start":849.201,"stop":849.931,"duration":0.73},{"text":"Against the I.J. Knight -- the receiver, I.J. --","start":849.931,"stop":853.503,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Personally?","start":853.503,"stop":855.03,"duration":1.53},{"text":"Personal liability?","start":855.03,"stop":858.836,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":858.836,"stop":859.627,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not a suit against the company?","start":859.627,"stop":861.866,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"It's against Francis Shunk Brown as receiver.","start":861.866,"stop":864.971,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":864.971,"stop":865.374,"duration":0.4},{"text":"That's an easy -- and to attempt to pass personal liability --","start":865.374,"stop":868.825,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Personal --","start":868.825,"stop":869.112,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to him.","start":869.112,"stop":869.944,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the liability.","start":869.944,"stop":870.957,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":870.957,"stop":871.448,"duration":0.49},{"text":"There are those the only two remedies that you can think of?","start":871.448,"stop":873.349,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Those are the only two remedies that I can think of.","start":873.349,"stop":875.55,"duration":2.2},{"text":"I think that it's the --","start":875.55,"stop":876.588,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And if he -- and if the trustee has to respond and Mr. Knight has to respond here, he has no recourse over against the estate of the company, does he?","start":876.588,"stop":888.557,"duration":11.97}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- Your Honor, it seems to me that if there were an estate of the company which survived liquidation as in Mr. White's suggestion yesterday of discovering the $10,500,000 goldmine, there's no question that the receiver standing in the position of the debtor that that estate would be liable and the Reading Company with its three million five would come out --","start":888.557,"stop":915.267,"duration":26.71}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if --","start":915.267,"stop":915.503,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- more than that.","start":915.503,"stop":915.717,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then that's just to ring around the rose, he had in that, not clear if that's a correct theory because what you're saying now -- the following, as I understand it, there's a fire caused by the negligence of the receiver.","start":915.717,"stop":929.789,"duration":14.07},{"text":"The receiver can be sued on his personal capacity.","start":929.789,"stop":934.602,"duration":4.81},{"text":"The receiver then has recourse over against the bankrupt estate.","start":934.602,"stop":941.004,"duration":6.4},{"text":"Now if that is so, then in that effect of this is that the bankrupt estate for whatever it may be, whatever may be in that estate is liable to the persons suffering from tort.","start":941.004,"stop":955.683,"duration":14.68}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a claim which isn't discharged by bankruptcy.","start":955.683,"stop":960.467,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what you are saying, it's a claim against the estate --","start":960.467,"stop":963.673,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":963.673,"stop":963.867,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and not just a claim against the receiver?","start":963.867,"stop":966.653,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a claim against the estate because the receiver in being sued stands in the position of the bankrupt under the Act.","start":966.653,"stop":974.166,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now what you're saying is that it's a -- it is not entitled.","start":974.166,"stop":979.248,"duration":5.08},{"text":"It's a claim, which is not entitled to -- Oh, it can't be that either.","start":979.248,"stop":984.135,"duration":4.89},{"text":"Suppose a receiver had judgments obtained against the receiver while the bankruptcy proceedings is still pending then the receiver has a claim over against the estate, you've tell me for -- to be made whole, is that right?","start":984.135,"stop":1001.517,"duration":17.38}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1001.517,"stop":1002.6,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now suppose the bankruptcy is still pending, he has at least a general claim against the estate.","start":1002.6,"stop":1009.866,"duration":7.27},{"text":"Does he have a priority claim as the cost of the administration?","start":1009.866,"stop":1013.75,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"He has no priority claim for where it say “negligence” claim --","start":1013.75,"stop":1017.423,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Or does -- where does he rank?","start":1017.423,"stop":1018.864,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- under the Act.","start":1018.864,"stop":1019.042,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Does this claim rank along with other creditors?","start":1019.042,"stop":1024.56,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Not having occur under the Act, not had the -- tort, not having occurred prior to the filing of petition and no suit having been, as the Act requires, filed and pending prior to the filing of this, he does not serve, he does not come in as a general creditor.","start":1024.56,"stop":1041.753,"duration":17.19}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And how does he come in?","start":1041.753,"stop":1042.431,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"He comes in as a claim, undischarged in bankruptcy because it is one not provable under the Act and would be on the same position as any negligent -- judgment creditor against an insolvent individual whether there had been no bankruptcy.","start":1042.431,"stop":1061.901,"duration":19.47},{"text":"This is a statutory proceeding and as this Court has repeatedly said, the -- there must be a convincing establishment of a right to this priority.","start":1061.901,"stop":1075.245,"duration":13.34},{"text":"And if you take the words of this Act, that the words of this Act as I have attempted to indicate if the only words that this can -- claim can be possibly be hang on are cost and expenses of administration.","start":1075.245,"stop":1092.352,"duration":17.11},{"text":"Now, cost and expenses of administration are defined by Section 62 subsection (a) (1) of the Act.","start":1092.352,"stop":1100.701,"duration":8.35},{"text":"The Act uses the words “the costs of administering this section of the Act”.","start":1100.701,"stop":1106.779,"duration":6.08},{"text":"It uses the word, “the cost of administering the estate” and it defines them as the actual and necessary cost incurred by officers other than referee in the administration of estates.","start":1106.779,"stop":1123.416,"duration":16.64},{"text":"The word “necessary” is again emphasized.","start":1123.416,"stop":1126.473,"duration":3.06},{"text":"It cannot be ignored and as I have said in my opinion, there is no necessity in negligence and necessary and negligence or antithetical words.","start":1126.473,"stop":1141.116,"duration":14.64},{"text":"An unliquidated tort claim such as this has no place in as a first priority.","start":1141.116,"stop":1149.804,"duration":8.69},{"text":"This is shown not only by the strict wording of the Act but is also shown by Congress' consideration of negligence claims here -- of tort claims in amendments of the Act and on occasions when it has considered amending the Act.","start":1149.804,"stop":1168.511,"duration":18.71},{"text":"This has occurred twice.","start":1168.511,"stop":1170.036,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"If this Chapter XI proceeding had succeeded and if the -- if there hadn't been a petition filed in ordinary bankruptcy, I suppose that this -- there could been a suit against the debtor, against the company.","start":1170.036,"stop":1185.774,"duration":15.74}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"There would have if the negligence which we've admitted been established in claims, they would have recovered out of the rehabilitated business.","start":1185.774,"stop":1193.886,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1193.886,"stop":1194.85,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"And probably the public liability policy.","start":1194.85,"stop":1198.21,"duration":3.36},{"text":"The receivers and trustees take public liability policies out and it is to this sort of reasonable, actual, necessary expense that these claims look.","start":1198.21,"stop":1210.702,"duration":12.49}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there insurance here?","start":1210.702,"stop":1211.851,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"Liability?","start":1211.851,"stop":1212.825,"duration":0.97},{"text":"Yes.","start":1212.825,"stop":1213.481,"duration":0.66},{"text":"Mr. Marx, who is my co-counsel here advised me there's a public liability policy but obviously not adequate enough for anything like this.","start":1213.481,"stop":1225.017,"duration":11.54},{"text":"And if Your Honor pleases, Congress has considered whether tort negative claims based on negligence should be even allowed in bankruptcy proceedings and in the Bankruptcy Act.","start":1225.017,"stop":1240.789,"duration":15.77},{"text":"In 1933, Congress considered and codified under the railroad reorganization section of the Act, giving a right to and giving a -- in this case, giving a priority to claims for personal injuries, to employees of a railroad corporation, claims of personal representatives of deceased employees of railroad corporations.","start":1240.789,"stop":1272.418,"duration":31.63},{"text":"This by Section 77 (n) gives a priority to these two tort claims in railroad reorganization.","start":1272.418,"stop":1283.339,"duration":10.92},{"text":"But note well, no priority is given to property damage claims based on negligence and no mention is made of property damage claims based on negligence.","start":1283.339,"stop":1295.986,"duration":12.65},{"text":"Congress was considering torts at that time.","start":1295.986,"stop":1299.69,"duration":3.7},{"text":"Now again, a year later, Congress considered --","start":1299.69,"stop":1301.872,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that amendment -- is that amendment relate only to claims for negligence in -- it was brought about by the receiver?","start":1301.872,"stop":1311.38,"duration":9.51}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"So I believe, Your Honor; in my reading of the section, yes.","start":1311.38,"stop":1318.323,"duration":6.94},{"text":"This is a case based of course on the continued operation of the railroad.","start":1318.323,"stop":1323.695,"duration":5.37},{"text":"This is a rehabilitation proceeding.","start":1323.695,"stop":1327.314,"duration":3.62},{"text":"If Your Honors, please, a year later in 1934, Congress provided by Section 63, subsection (a) (7) that claims in negligence where the suit had been pending prior, have been instituted and pending, prior to the institution of the petition, were provable claims and those are the only negligence claim which are provable claims in a liquidating bankruptcy and it is only by Section 62 subsection (a) (1) that cost and expense of administration are provable.","start":1327.314,"stop":1382.067,"duration":54.75},{"text":"And that Section limits those provable costs and expenses to actual and necessary ones.","start":1382.067,"stop":1389.465,"duration":7.4},{"text":"If Your Honor pleases, the history of the Bankruptcy Act, the policy of the Bankruptcy Act, which is to preserve an estate for liquidation and the wording of the Act, I submit all, on all three grounds, show that this claim does -- is not a claim which convincingly can be established as a priority claim and to grant it would frustrate the policy which Congress has established.","start":1389.465,"stop":1429.909,"duration":40.44},{"text":"It may be wrong philosophically but it is a policy established by Congress in the wording of this Act and allows and makes no provision for claims such as this.","start":1429.909,"stop":1443.954,"duration":14.04},{"text":"To grant it would frustrate the Act completely.","start":1443.954,"stop":1447.176,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honors.","start":1447.176,"stop":1455.956,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Roberts?","start":1455.956,"stop":1456.641,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1456.641,"stop":1460.978,"duration":4.34},{"text":"There are several results that this Court could reach in this case.","start":1460.978,"stop":1465.502,"duration":4.52},{"text":"The Government submits and agrees verily that this is not a proper cost of administration entitled to a class 1 priority.","start":1465.502,"stop":1476.966,"duration":11.46},{"text":"The purpose of the Chapter XI proceeding is to rehabilitate a distressed organization.","start":1476.966,"stop":1486.653,"duration":9.69},{"text":"It allows as cost of administration those expenses that are necessary to rehabilitate the corporate -- either a corporation or an individual.","start":1486.653,"stop":1498.878,"duration":12.22},{"text":"Chapter XI proceedings are separate and distinct from Chapter X reorganizations.","start":1498.878,"stop":1506.352,"duration":7.47},{"text":"For instance, in Chapter X, Section 64 priorities do not apply.","start":1506.352,"stop":1513.399,"duration":7.05},{"text":"Also by statute in Chapter X reorganizations, Congress has made the equity receivership rules applicable.","start":1513.399,"stop":1522.783,"duration":9.38},{"text":"It says the Court shall sit and have the powers of a receiver in equity.","start":1522.783,"stop":1527.948,"duration":5.17},{"text":"And that I think is why you find that in some aspects in bankruptcy, they refer to the receivership cases.","start":1527.948,"stop":1535.915,"duration":7.97},{"text":"In fact, the case cited by Collier for his proposition that negligence are allowable as priority claims in cost of administration is a railroad receivership case.","start":1535.915,"stop":1549.064,"duration":13.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, mister, you -- would you hazard against us to what would happen to this claim in a Chapter X case?","start":1549.064,"stop":1556.474,"duration":7.41}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In a Chapter X case in this -- I really do not know, Mr. Justice White what would happen in a Chapter X reorganization proceeding.","start":1556.474,"stop":1566.807,"duration":10.33},{"text":"There are several.","start":1566.807,"stop":1567.489,"duration":0.68},{"text":"There is no tri-parties schedule.","start":1567.489,"stop":1570.79,"duration":3.3},{"text":"In the equity --","start":1570.79,"stop":1571.664,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn't that --","start":1571.664,"stop":1572.214,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- railroad receiverships, however, Mr. Justice White, they rank the priorities and there's cost to administration.","start":1572.214,"stop":1580.791,"duration":8.58},{"text":"If you read the railroad cases that had been cited, they refer their bond holders who are contending that they come ahead of certain classes of creditors.","start":1580.791,"stop":1591.712,"duration":10.92},{"text":"In those cases --","start":1591.712,"stop":1591.963,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What claims are -- tort claims are connected with operating a business aren't normally cost of administration of some kind or in -- or in -- but or rather in railroad reorganizations.","start":1591.963,"stop":1604.384,"duration":12.42}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In railroad reorganization --","start":1604.384,"stop":1604.774,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And I thought only in Chapter X.","start":1604.774,"stop":1606.778,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"They're not referred to, however, Your Honor, as cost of administration.","start":1606.778,"stop":1610.052,"duration":3.27},{"text":"If you read the cases, they list their cost of administration and then they come down and generally surround the fourth or fifth class; that they refer to tort claims are allowed ahead of bond holders of the corporation.","start":1610.052,"stop":1624.28,"duration":14.23},{"text":"They do not refer to them specifically as cost of administration is.","start":1624.28,"stop":1628.392,"duration":4.11},{"text":"I read those cases.","start":1628.392,"stop":1629.914,"duration":1.52},{"text":"They rank them much in the same way as Section 64 and Chapter XI rank certain classes of creditors.","start":1629.914,"stop":1636.476,"duration":6.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Collier seems to think that tort claims are payable as a cost of administration in Chapter X.","start":1636.476,"stop":1644.432,"duration":7.96}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In Chapter X, yes then he cites --","start":1644.432,"stop":1646.171,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"As and the -- if they are, it's because they are necessary incidence to the running of the business.","start":1646.171,"stop":1654.62,"duration":8.45}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"And I think -- as we point out, we believe that some tort claims could be allowable in this type of proceeding where they are necessary, where they are covered -- could be covered by a liability insurance, for instance in a cab operation.","start":1654.62,"stop":1670.918,"duration":16.3},{"text":"Surely the city or municipality where the cab company is operating requires liability insurance.","start":1670.918,"stop":1677.894,"duration":6.98},{"text":"I do not believe that a trustee could ignore that requirement and I don't think the insurance company could defend on the ground for the trustee is not liable for torts.","start":1677.894,"stop":1689.868,"duration":11.97},{"text":"I think that the trustee's insurance would cover in those instances.","start":1689.868,"stop":1694.96,"duration":5.09},{"text":"And I believe that in this --","start":1694.96,"stop":1697.047,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Performance bond too?","start":1697.047,"stop":1699.155,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":1699.155,"stop":1699.386,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Performance bond too with the (Inaudible)?","start":1699.386,"stop":1700.977,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think the performance bond could be looked to.","start":1700.977,"stop":1703.953,"duration":2.98},{"text":"In fact, there is one company here who is suing the trustee and I assume they are looking to his performance bond as one of the means of recovering.","start":1703.953,"stop":1713.754,"duration":9.8},{"text":"I think also that they would look to the bankrupt.","start":1713.754,"stop":1717.055,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Now, in this instance, absent -- the negligence claims, as I total the claims, an absence -- tremendous administrative expenses, which are not as yet -- have not as yet been allowed.","start":1717.055,"stop":1731.202,"duration":14.15},{"text":"There will be a sum remaining in this bankruptcy.","start":1731.202,"stop":1736.703,"duration":5.5},{"text":"If you total the creditors, they are less in total amount than their limits as we understand that it will be recovered under the fire insurance so that there would be an amount that would go back to the bankrupt if he were discharged; if there were no other claim.","start":1736.703,"stop":1753.788,"duration":17.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the estate now just the proceeds of the insurance?","start":1753.788,"stop":1757.029,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand, it's just the proceeds to the insurance.","start":1757.029,"stop":1759.455,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the ground or the land?","start":1759.455,"stop":1763.23,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"May answer Your Honor, in -- the city has condemned the land.","start":1763.23,"stop":1766.941,"duration":3.71},{"text":"The proceeds of that will be --","start":1766.941,"stop":1768.314,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":1768.314,"stop":1768.524,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Owen B. Rhoads","textObjs":[{"text":"-- part of the estate.","start":1768.524,"stop":1770.982,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we believe that this Court in Nicholas has lead away to the -- a way that the court claimant here could have recovered or could have at least presented his claim if he had met the requirements of 63, Section 63 of the Bankruptcy Act.","start":1770.982,"stop":1796.8,"duration":25.82},{"text":"And that is --","start":1796.8,"stop":1797.842,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The problem with that, Mr. Roberts is, isn't it that 63 talks exclusively about claims against the bankrupt?","start":1797.842,"stop":1805.962,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct Your Honor, but I don't believe that --","start":1805.962,"stop":1809.112,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And Nicholas doesn't deal with that?","start":1809.112,"stop":1810.973,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it doesn't deal with that but I do not believe that it would do violence to the Bankruptcy Act to interpret that there are the three separate periods, which is the periods, free bankruptcy, there is the Chapter XI arrangement period and then there's this great bankruptcy period.","start":1810.973,"stop":1828.976,"duration":18},{"text":"And if you do that, then a tort claim would -- during the Chapter XI reorganization would come in as a general creditor.","start":1828.976,"stop":1837.515,"duration":8.54},{"text":"And we feel that that is the equitable result to reach in this type of situation that there he shares with the other general creditors.","start":1837.515,"stop":1846.21,"duration":8.69},{"text":"It is merely happen -- instance that one tort claimant would be three-bankruptcy and another one, Chapter XI reorg -- arrangement proceeding, tort claimant.","start":1846.21,"stop":1859.686,"duration":13.48},{"text":"In fact, in many cases, Mr. Justice White point out it is a debtor in possession who is operating the business and it's the same person operating the business who is -- who operated three Chapter XI arrangements.","start":1859.686,"stop":1873.68,"duration":13.99},{"text":"And we feel that in no circumstances where there is a Chapter XI that it would no violence to the statute.","start":1873.68,"stop":1880.78,"duration":7.1},{"text":"To read 63 as being applicable and that the bankrupt includes the period pre straight bankruptcy.","start":1880.78,"stop":1888.596,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, even so in this particular case the Reading Company couldn't get a benefit of that because they didn't sue in time, isn't that correct?","start":1888.596,"stop":1896.827,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"They didn't sue in time but I don't believe that that would preclude them completely, Your Honor.","start":1896.827,"stop":1902.26,"duration":5.43},{"text":"It might rank them below the other general creditors who've had then diligent and who have sued.","start":1902.26,"stop":1907.953,"duration":5.69},{"text":"Well, I submit that it's no different than a tort claimant who might have had the same thing happen three days prearrangement in any circumstances.","start":1907.953,"stop":1917.848,"duration":9.89},{"text":"There are some creditors who are not going to get paid and will not get paid in full.","start":1917.848,"stop":1923.351,"duration":5.5},{"text":"That is the purpose of an arrangement, so that a distressed business when it is technically insolvent can arrange its affair so that it may survive in the business world.","start":1923.351,"stop":1936.71,"duration":13.36},{"text":"And it's the intent of Congress that that type of business should survive.","start":1936.71,"stop":1942.469,"duration":5.76},{"text":"It was the intent of Congress in passing the Chapter XI arrangement proceeding that they have a way of arranging their businesses.","start":1942.469,"stop":1952.38,"duration":9.91},{"text":"A creditors get together -- you know, I'm sure and arrange what they would take on their claims.","start":1952.38,"stop":1959.46,"duration":7.08},{"text":"Now, it's interesting to note that on the issue of whether or not there's a constitutional right to a recovery.","start":1959.46,"stop":1967.78,"duration":8.32},{"text":"It seems to me that the cases in bankruptcy involving a landlord which are discussed in the Connor case in this Court cited in our brief, where the landlord had no recovery whatsoever, this is the instance -- for instance where the premises are leased to a business for a long period of time, that business goes bankrupt.","start":1967.78,"stop":1996.595,"duration":28.82},{"text":"The trustee can reject the lease and that's an action of the trustee in rejecting a lease not the bankrupt.","start":1996.595,"stop":2006.997,"duration":10.4},{"text":"Now, prior to an amendment to 77 of the Bankruptcy Act, the landlord had to look as this Court said to the empty shell, the corporation for any recovery, there was no recovery whatsoever.","start":2006.997,"stop":2023.588,"duration":16.59},{"text":"Congress then allowed, taking that that was an equitable to allow him no recovery, then amended Section 77 of the Bankruptcy Act to allow a three-month period of rent to the landlord.","start":2023.588,"stop":2039.72,"duration":16.13},{"text":"This Court upheld that section and said there was no constitutional restriction of that type on the lease; that the landlord was not entitled to damages for the full term of the lease and we submit that there's no problem here in this respect.","start":2039.72,"stop":2058.376,"duration":18.66}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Roberts, what would you say if this had been a small fire and the damage is $12,000 to a -- $10,000 to adjoining property and the Chapter XI proceeding just continued on and that -- what would've happened to that $10,000 claim?","start":2058.376,"stop":2075.971,"duration":17.59}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that it would have been settled as other claims of the bankrupt are settled, Your Honor.","start":2075.971,"stop":2081.291,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And what do you mean by that?","start":2081.291,"stop":2082.625,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in a -- rather -- other, oh it is a bankrupt in the --","start":2082.625,"stop":2087.952,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, it's just --","start":2087.952,"stop":2088.496,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the arrangement proceeding.","start":2088.496,"stop":2089.657,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's say the other debts of the debtor had been extended for five years and the person who is damaged, $10,000 worth by the operation of the building by the trustee wants immediate payment.","start":2089.657,"stop":2108.073,"duration":18.42},{"text":"They say this is an expense of administration which must be paid along with other expenses of administration.","start":2108.073,"stop":2113.054,"duration":4.98},{"text":"That means now not five years from now.","start":2113.054,"stop":2117.704,"duration":4.65},{"text":"And the question is, is it an expense of administration under Chapter XI proceeding?","start":2117.704,"stop":2123.334,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"My answer to that is no, it's not an expense of administration, Your Honor.","start":2123.334,"stop":2126.936,"duration":3.6},{"text":"It would be looked on under our view in this way, he could sue the trustee and then if the business then goes into straight bankruptcy, he would be --","start":2126.936,"stop":2137.597,"duration":10.66}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Never does, --","start":2137.597,"stop":2138.536,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":2138.536,"stop":2139.974,"duration":1.44},{"text":"But if he does, he would come under 63 but by not -- either him not putting it on the straight bankruptcy or other creditors not putting the bankrupt into straight bankruptcy.","start":2139.974,"stop":2150.931,"duration":10.96},{"text":"Our position is that he would then share, he would be one of the creditors who will be dealt with in the arrangement proceedings.","start":2150.931,"stop":2159.631,"duration":8.7},{"text":"Now, whether he accepts the proceedings or not, as I read the arrangement, Chapter XI arrangement, the court may approve a proceeding if a majority of the creditors approve it.","start":2159.631,"stop":2172.046,"duration":12.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course, the arrangement's already been approved and the -- in my example, he filed the plan, it's being carried out.","start":2172.046,"stop":2183.356,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"And there's -- the trustee has been discharged there.","start":2183.356,"stop":2185.174,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":2185.174,"stop":2187.497,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Why I think of the plan -- if everything has worked out, as I understand Chapter XI proceedings, if everything is worked out, business is turned back to the debtor and he operates normally, it's not by trustee.","start":2187.497,"stop":2202.002,"duration":14.51}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that -- you think the tort claim though is at -- that $10,000 tort claim is recoverable somehow from the debtor or from the trustee in a Chapter XI proceeding?","start":2202.002,"stop":2213.745,"duration":11.74}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"If the remedy is there, whether it's recoverable or not will depend on the amount of money available.","start":2213.745,"stop":2219.256,"duration":5.51},{"text":"Yes.","start":2219.256,"stop":2219.418,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's assume the -- well, its recoverable, as it's recoverable as the rest of the debts.","start":2219.418,"stop":2223.514,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"As the rests of the debts, yes.","start":2223.514,"stop":2225.039,"duration":1.53},{"text":"It would then be --","start":2225.039,"stop":2225.447,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You would get -- you just -- your argument is that it just doesn't get priority?","start":2225.447,"stop":2229.019,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2229.019,"stop":2229.825,"duration":0.81},{"text":"We say --","start":2229.825,"stop":2230.384,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it's provable in a Chapter XI.","start":2230.384,"stop":2233.624,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think its provable if -- and then if he depends whether if its provable in a straight bankruptcy it would depend on whether or not they had started their suit as 63 requires prior to the straight bankruptcy being filed.","start":2233.624,"stop":2251.585,"duration":17.96},{"text":"I don't believe that a trustee can operate a business and not have claims against him provable.","start":2251.585,"stop":2259.306,"duration":7.72},{"text":"I don't believe that Act should be read that way.","start":2259.306,"stop":2261.636,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well what If it is provable -- if its provable in Chapter XI -- that claim is provable in Chapter XI had there been no bankruptcy?","start":2261.636,"stop":2270.79,"duration":9.15},{"text":"I don't see why it isn't for that very reason, wholly aside from 63 (a) (7) provable in bankruptcy.","start":2270.79,"stop":2276.963,"duration":6.17},{"text":"If bankruptcy ensued?","start":2276.963,"stop":2279.107,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"It's provable in bankruptcy but you have to meet certain conditions to be provable in bankruptcy and they have to meet those conditions.","start":2279.107,"stop":2284.717,"duration":5.61},{"text":"If they meet those conditions, we submit under our argument that they would be provable.","start":2284.717,"stop":2293.62,"duration":8.9},{"text":"And we feel that --","start":2293.62,"stop":2295.403,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But even in your argument as to -- under 63 (a) (7) since the suite was not filed in time here, this petitioner, the Reading Company, it can't take advantage of that and so in this case, what is your theory?","start":2295.403,"stop":2309.781,"duration":14.38}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case, my theory is --","start":2309.781,"stop":2311.329,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"As to which remedy, do you think?","start":2311.329,"stop":2312.593,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"If as to which remedy is sue the trustee and then when there is an overages, there will be in this case.","start":2312.593,"stop":2321.1,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And it will -- and this will --","start":2321.1,"stop":2321.956,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"It will share in that.","start":2321.956,"stop":2323.393,"duration":1.44},{"text":"Now, counsel for the bank, for the claimant --","start":2323.393,"stop":2327.577,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"After discharge, you mean after discharge there will be a --","start":2327.577,"stop":2331.754,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"There'll be -- there's a sum of money available.","start":2331.754,"stop":2333.77,"duration":2.02},{"text":"If I read that the claims have been totaled correctly, and I believe that they have.","start":2333.77,"stop":2339.282,"duration":5.51},{"text":"And I do not believe the cost of administration although there are litigation expenses I have no idea what the court is going to allow as a cost of administration.","start":2339.282,"stop":2348.098,"duration":8.82},{"text":"But assume that the cost of administration is not great enough to eat up what's left, there will be something here for these claimants.","start":2348.098,"stop":2357.331,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Now, yesterday --","start":2357.331,"stop":2357.951,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And what -- because there'll be something which -- to which it is entitled, why?","start":2357.951,"stop":2363.898,"duration":5.95},{"text":"Because they have claims that survived bankruptcy not having been provable in bankruptcy?","start":2363.898,"stop":2368.917,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sure Your Honor.","start":2368.917,"stop":2371.559,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's --","start":2371.559,"stop":2371.794,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the reason it would be -- it would survive bankruptcy where it's not proved.","start":2371.794,"stop":2374.35,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Because --","start":2374.35,"stop":2374.821,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Any claim that's not provable is not discharged.","start":2374.821,"stop":2377.08,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know that.","start":2377.08,"stop":2377.742,"duration":0.66},{"text":"But this -- this of course, was not a claim and negligence against the bankrupt and that's the kind that survived.","start":2377.742,"stop":2383.578,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In this -- well, this Court has passed on this question on several railroad cases where the bankrupt -- after the bankruptcy proceeding, after the trustee, and equity receivership there.","start":2383.578,"stop":2398.629,"duration":15.05},{"text":"It would've -- property was given back to the owner and the claims against the trustee for them allowable against the property although it was the negligence of the trustee.","start":2398.629,"stop":2412.152,"duration":13.52},{"text":"They're Texas and Pacific Railway Company, the Johnson at 151 U.S., 81, and another Texas in Pacific Railway versus Bloom at 164 U.S. 636.","start":2412.152,"stop":2428.391,"duration":16.24},{"text":"Now, I believe that in that instance and in the instance that was resided yesterday where goldmine is found and there's $10,000,000 in that goldmine, I can't believe that the court is not going to allow the claim to be presented against the bankrupt.","start":2428.391,"stop":2447.233,"duration":18.84}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't' believe that the trustee has personal liability even after he's discharged?","start":2447.233,"stop":2453.631,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Personal liability, I think that would depend on the negligence, Your Honor, and that has not been litigated here as to what the negligence were.","start":2453.631,"stop":2460.793,"duration":7.16},{"text":"The allegations of negligence, I doubt very seriously, that they would warrant a personal liability of the trustee.","start":2460.793,"stop":2467.697,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Because I got the -- presume that the preceding counsel took the opposite view.","start":2467.697,"stop":2476.016,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"He said the bond, if I understood, he said that the bond would be --","start":2476.016,"stop":2479.702,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But then he went further than that and said that there would be personal liability on the part of the receiver and I gather that, perhaps wrong, that his position was that -- to me personal liability on the part of the receiver even if there were no willfulness that it's just straight negligence.","start":2479.702,"stop":2499.467,"duration":19.76}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I did not understand his argument to be that the receiver here would be personally liable for these acts.","start":2499.467,"stop":2505.879,"duration":6.41},{"text":"I don't' think you would have a receiver to qualify under those circumstances.","start":2505.879,"stop":2510.864,"duration":4.99},{"text":"I think people would shy away for the receivership.","start":2510.864,"stop":2515.216,"duration":4.35},{"text":"If that's the outcome of this case, that it's -- he is to be personally liable, just like I think that if these are allowed as administration expenses, many attorneys are going to hesitate to tell other claimants or other would be claimants then suppliers and whatnot to do business in a Chapter XI arrangement, which is really the purpose of administration expenses or allowing them as administration expenses as to encourage them to do business with the bankrupt or the distressed business.","start":2515.216,"stop":2547.825,"duration":32.61},{"text":"And if anyone who is a lawyer in private practice was approached by a supplier, was advised, “Should I extend credit to the trustee?”","start":2547.825,"stop":2557.34,"duration":9.52},{"text":"He's going to have to consider then what are the possible limits of the damage claim if there may be and he'd have to consider the type of business and anything else because here, the people who would extend their credit and who have attempted to assist in rehabilitating the bankrupt are going to have to share pro rata if these are administration expenses.","start":2557.34,"stop":2580.122,"duration":22.78},{"text":"And they would be penalized.","start":2580.122,"stop":2582.132,"duration":2.01},{"text":"And I think that this Third Circuit of the lower court here were correct in denying these claims as priority claims.","start":2582.132,"stop":2589.01,"duration":6.88}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, but let me see if I correctly understand your position.","start":2589.01,"stop":2594.467,"duration":5.46},{"text":"Your position is that Chapter XI proceeding is pending, if the litigation has started on a tort claim prior to bankruptcy, the Chapter XI merging into a bankruptcy proceeding, then by virtue of 63 (a), that's provable, right?","start":2594.467,"stop":2615.535,"duration":21.07},{"text":"That's point one.","start":2615.535,"stop":2616.102,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2616.102,"stop":2617.57,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Point 2, if Chapter XI and it goes on to the end, an arrangement among creditors, without any bankruptcy proceeding then hopefully the tort claim will be settled out whether or not a suit has been filed just by an informal arrangements among claimants, is that right?","start":2617.57,"stop":2639.252,"duration":21.68}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2639.252,"stop":2640.795,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"If it is not settled out, this is third possibility, in the Chapter XI proceeding.","start":2640.795,"stop":2648.628,"duration":7.83},{"text":"And if the Chapter XI proceeding does not merge into a bankruptcy or the next, if the litigation has not begun before bankruptcy, then the claim survives against the company as it immerges from the Chapter XI or straight bankruptcy proceedings.","start":2648.628,"stop":2676.776,"duration":28.15},{"text":"In that event, until your position is and until -- at least until the trustee is discharged, a suit may be brought against the trustee.","start":2676.776,"stop":2688.028,"duration":11.25},{"text":"Recovery may -- do you think be had on his bond?","start":2688.028,"stop":2692.863,"duration":4.84},{"text":"That liability of the trustee may be established than that may -- a claim may thereby be asserted against the bankrupt estate?","start":2692.863,"stop":2705.47,"duration":12.61},{"text":"Have I summarized that correctly or am I wrong?","start":2705.47,"stop":2709.586,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2709.586,"stop":2710.084,"duration":0.5},{"text":"Although I believe that if he had presented his claim as a creditor in the arrangement proceeding, that he would be bound by that proceeding.","start":2710.084,"stop":2722.702,"duration":12.62}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he wouldn't --","start":2722.702,"stop":2723.243,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":2723.243,"stop":2723.334,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"He's just a claimant.","start":2723.334,"stop":2725.926,"duration":2.59},{"text":"In my case, he had introduced his tort claim, the judgment.","start":2725.926,"stop":2731.615,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he's just a creditor.","start":2731.615,"stop":2733.105,"duration":1.49},{"text":"It would not then -- I -- you've correctly summarized our position.","start":2733.105,"stop":2736.046,"duration":2.94},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2736.046,"stop":2740.733,"duration":4.69},{"text":"May I just tell a moment to reply to --","start":2740.733,"stop":2743.519,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course you have a few moments to reply.","start":2743.519,"stop":2747.307,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you sir.","start":2747.307,"stop":2749.23,"duration":1.92},{"text":"Actually, Justice Fortas, we did present our claim during the arrangement proceeding.","start":2749.23,"stop":2757.193,"duration":7.96},{"text":"It was not until after these claims were presented.","start":2757.193,"stop":2761.32,"duration":4.13},{"text":"Not -- It was not until May, this fire occurred in January; that the company went into bankruptcy and we considered that by presenting this claim, we were doing the equivalent, starting a suit.","start":2761.32,"stop":2778.212,"duration":16.89},{"text":"Now, I would like to lie to rest the contention that we have a right, first of all, against the bankrupt.","start":2778.212,"stop":2787.119,"duration":8.91},{"text":"I do not sincerely believe we could possibly have a claim because for six weeks, he had been out of control.","start":2787.119,"stop":2795.332,"duration":8.21},{"text":"He had no control whatever over what was done in that building.","start":2795.332,"stop":2799.953,"duration":4.62},{"text":"This was an engineer who was hired by the receiver and I do not see how we could hold the bankrupt responsible.","start":2799.953,"stop":2809.151,"duration":9.2},{"text":"Now, our claim was, as I say presented before the bankruptcy occurred.","start":2809.151,"stop":2815.932,"duration":6.78},{"text":"It has been expunged both as a general claim and as an administrative expense and we have -- we are now out of the bankruptcy proceeding unless the judgment is reversed.","start":2815.932,"stop":2829.345,"duration":13.41},{"text":"We just simply had no standing whatever.","start":2829.345,"stop":2832.851,"duration":3.51},{"text":"Now, as far as 63 (a) (7) is concerned, that appears at page 24 of our brief, this is the brief for petition and it says, “Debts of the bankrupt may be proved and allowed against this estate which are founded upon the following things.”","start":2832.851,"stop":2859.216,"duration":26.36},{"text":"Now, if I am correct and I don't see how I can be wrong about the -- whether this is a claim against the bankrupt, if I am correct, then certainly, we have no claim under the Section 63 because this covers only “debts of the bankrupt”.","start":2859.216,"stop":2875.993,"duration":16.78},{"text":"Now the only other place we have to go is cost and expenses of administration.","start":2875.993,"stop":2881.393,"duration":5.4},{"text":"There is no other place.","start":2881.393,"stop":2884.338,"duration":2.95},{"text":"For claims against the receiver which arise during the course of the arrangement or during the course of bankruptcy, and well I must confess that this action was started by my Brother, I didn't start this myself, and when I first heard that he had started a claim, this was expenses of administration, I had the same reaction that some of Your Honors have had to it that a $3,500,000 doesn't sound like an expense of administration.","start":2884.338,"stop":2916.675,"duration":32.34},{"text":"But the more I have lived with this thing, I can't ask Your Honors, to spend the amount of time thinking about that I have.","start":2916.675,"stop":2922.834,"duration":6.16},{"text":"But I am so sure that this can't be anything else.","start":2922.834,"stop":2926.865,"duration":4.03},{"text":"There's no other place to go.","start":2926.865,"stop":2928.243,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what about the other theory that's been discussed here this morning, that this is to say that this is a tort committed by the trustee, receiver trustee, that an action may be brought against him and that the recovery and it went to -- his liability is established, there -- recovery can be had and he has a claim over against the estate.","start":2928.243,"stop":2963.755,"duration":35.51}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well Your Honor, that is the law --","start":2963.755,"stop":2965.072,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what you understand of defense just in here?","start":2965.072,"stop":2968.695,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that that is their contention, sir, yes but this is -- this has been the law of some states.","start":2968.695,"stop":2974.975,"duration":6.28},{"text":"It was for example, the law of New York when Vass against Conron Brothers was decided.","start":2974.975,"stop":2981.068,"duration":6.09},{"text":"But it is not as I understand the federal law.","start":2981.068,"stop":2984.397,"duration":3.33},{"text":"This Court as -- long ago as I think 141 U.S. held that a receiver cannot be personally liable.","start":2984.397,"stop":2991.662,"duration":7.26},{"text":"It was a rather old fashion than rather a devious method.","start":2991.662,"stop":2994.262,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are two things here.","start":2994.262,"stop":2995.69,"duration":1.43},{"text":"One, that is to be personally liable and then a variant of that suggested by counsel for the Government that he could be sued and that a liability would be -- would then be after judgment was obtained against the trustee, a liability will then be the liability of the estate.","start":2995.69,"stop":3019.748,"duration":24.06}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we --","start":3019.748,"stop":3021.308,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I must confess, I'm a little confused as to --","start":3021.308,"stop":3023.792,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"We have --","start":3023.792,"stop":3024.627,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- precise meaning of these two --","start":3024.627,"stop":3026.709,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"We have cited a case at the end of our -- I think it's in our reply brief, which holds that the fact that you got a judgment in a separate action -- law, establishes only the amount of the damages but also that you have a claim against the tortfeasor but unless -- or if -- or some other type of claim.","start":3026.709,"stop":3056.059,"duration":29.35},{"text":"But unless the claim which gave rise to the judgment is itself provable, the judgment is not provable by just automatically.","start":3056.059,"stop":3066.202,"duration":10.14},{"text":"In other words, it doesn't -- we take the position that we have done the equivalent of suing by presenting this claim for - -- we of course, we have turned to the administrative expenses but it was expunged not only for that but under 63 (a) (7).","start":3066.202,"stop":3083.212,"duration":17.01},{"text":"Now, the Government originally said, “Well, that's quite right” and then now they say, “Well, we could have sued under 63 (a) (7)” and as I hope I have demonstrated to Your Honors, I just don't believe that we have any such thing.","start":3083.212,"stop":3095.898,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the tort had at this part, it had occurred three days before the Chapter XI proceeding and no question with that -- it would have been a tort that would not -- there would've been a claim not provable in Chapter XI or subsequent bankruptcy.","start":3095.898,"stop":3112.628,"duration":16.73}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"And as we brought suit, that's correct, sir.","start":3112.628,"stop":3114.522,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":3114.522,"stop":3115.042,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct --","start":3115.042,"stop":3116.007,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless you have brought suit before the petition was filed.","start":3116.007,"stop":3118.435,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as long -- I have always questioned whether 63 (a) (7) would stand up if somebody really wanted to give it to give it back.","start":3118.435,"stop":3123.948,"duration":5.51}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, but that was -- that's what statute said, didn't it?","start":3123.948,"stop":3126.415,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes sir.","start":3126.415,"stop":3127.137,"duration":0.72},{"text":"It says that.","start":3127.137,"stop":3128.015,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, so that the schemes of statutes are arguable as such you draw a line, you erect a Chinese wall at the date of the filing of the petition insofar as tort claims are concerned?","start":3128.015,"stop":3144.281,"duration":16.27}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3144.281,"stop":3146.145,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now here, you have a tort that occurred during the period of the administration under Chapter XI and you are saying that the -- that does not -- that tort claim does not survive.","start":3146.145,"stop":3161.247,"duration":15.1},{"text":"That's not a claim against the debtor as the debtor emerges from Chapter XI or from the subsequent bankruptcy proceeding.","start":3161.247,"stop":3170.871,"duration":9.62}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's my position exactly, sir.","start":3170.871,"stop":3172.489,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And you say that also you have no claim against the trustee personally?","start":3172.489,"stop":3179.303,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":3179.303,"stop":3180.934,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And that unless you have a claim against the assets, against the bankrupt or the debtor under Chapter XI that you have no recourse whatsoever?","start":3180.934,"stop":3194.063,"duration":13.13}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly our positions here that we -- that these people -- we, and everybody that -- because we represent now, this whole $3,500,000 in claims.","start":3194.063,"stop":3203.632,"duration":9.57},{"text":"If this case falls, nobody gets a nickel.","start":3203.632,"stop":3207.33,"duration":3.7},{"text":"This is our position out of this estate.","start":3207.33,"stop":3211.798,"duration":4.47},{"text":"There may be -- there's some insurance proceeds.","start":3211.798,"stop":3213.249,"duration":1.45},{"text":"This is the first time I've heard that there was policy, which I think we would be entitled to.","start":3213.249,"stop":3224.451,"duration":11.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I haven't --","start":3224.451,"stop":3227.443,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Richard M. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the question, of course -- there would be a question as to whether the insurance covers the trustee.","start":3227.443,"stop":3232.41,"duration":4.97},{"text":"I guess it does.","start":3232.41,"stop":3233.956,"duration":1.55},{"text":"But at least -- we will sue the receiver on the grounds not that he personally did anything but that his agent was negligent.","start":3233.956,"stop":3242.994,"duration":9.04},{"text":"That is our theory against the receiver.","start":3242.994,"stop":3246.183,"duration":3.19},{"text":"Thank you very much, sir.","start":3246.183,"stop":3247.844,"duration":1.66}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 04, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/15439","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No. 127, Reading Company, petitioner, versus Francis Shunk Brown, 3d, etc.","start":0,"stop":21.814,"duration":21.81},{"text":"Mr. White, you may proceed with your argument.","start":21.814,"stop":24.703,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and if the Court please.","start":24.703,"stop":28.089,"duration":3.39},{"text":"This is a petition for the review of the judgment of the Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit, a bankruptcy case.","start":28.089,"stop":36.288,"duration":8.2},{"text":"And the issue before the court is whether a claim for damages arising out of the negligence of the receiver while operating a business during in -- a Chapter XI proceeding, what subsequently became a bankruptcy.","start":36.288,"stop":53.107,"duration":16.82},{"text":"Is an expense of administration with the priority to which such expenses are entitled or whatever it has no standing whatever.","start":53.107,"stop":64.084,"duration":10.98},{"text":"The I.J. Knight Realty Corporation owned and operated an eight-story industrial building in Philadelphia known as the Fretz Building.","start":64.084,"stop":73.496,"duration":9.41},{"text":"And on November the 16th 1962, Knight filed a petition for arrangement under Chapter XI and the District Court for the Houston District appointed a receiver and authorized him to operate the business which he proceeded to do.","start":73.496,"stop":92.571,"duration":19.08},{"text":"Six weeks later, on the first of January 1963, the Fretz Building was totally destroyed by a disastrous fire which has been described as the worst fire that Philadelphia ever had.","start":92.571,"stop":105.88,"duration":13.31},{"text":"And a large number of adjoining structures were destroyed and damaged including a property going to the Reading Company.","start":105.88,"stop":117.347,"duration":11.47},{"text":"The receivership was subsequently terminated and Knight was adjudicated of bankrupt and Brown was then elected trustee.","start":117.347,"stop":126.074,"duration":8.73},{"text":"The Reading Company and over a hundred other property owners whose property was destroyed in the fire filed claims as administrative expenses due the negligence of the receiver.","start":126.074,"stop":138.274,"duration":12.2},{"text":"And the trustee thereafter petitioned the referee to expunge the crime not only as an expense of administration but also as a general unsecured claim.","start":138.274,"stop":150.975,"duration":12.7},{"text":"The referee did expunge the claims, expunged the Reading Company claim and he also ruled that the Reading Claim should be a test case for all of the hundred some odd other cases.","start":150.975,"stop":165.832,"duration":14.86},{"text":"There are approximately three and a half million dollars in claims.","start":165.832,"stop":170.168,"duration":4.34},{"text":"The assets -- the estimate at the time, the record was prepared, were between $638,045 and I believe that the -- that figure is more nearly correct.","start":170.168,"stop":185.235,"duration":15.07},{"text":"The Government is in this case because it has a tax claim of some $245,000 relating to the pre-petitioned period and there were other claims amounting to about $378,000.","start":185.235,"stop":200.471,"duration":15.24},{"text":"The District Court for the Houston District affirmed the referee and the Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit affirmed the District Court with three judges dissenting.","start":200.471,"stop":211.372,"duration":10.9},{"text":"This Court granted certiorari on the 16th of October 1962.","start":211.372,"stop":216.352,"duration":4.98},{"text":"And for purposes of this case, it is admitted that this fire was caused when an engineer hired by the receiver accidentally attached a portable heater to high-tension wires while working on some frozen sprinkler pipes.","start":216.352,"stop":233.338,"duration":16.99},{"text":"Knight had been out of possession as I said for approximately six weeks so that the bankrupt could not be held responsible for the engineer's negligence.","start":233.338,"stop":244.515,"duration":11.18},{"text":"A consequent -- this is a claim against the receiver as such and has in our view an entirely different character from claims against the bankrupt which arose prior to the bankruptcy proceedings.","start":244.515,"stop":259.539,"duration":15.02},{"text":"Now the cost of expenses of administration are provided for in Section 64a (1) of the Bankruptcy Act.","start":259.539,"stop":267.757,"duration":8.22},{"text":"That Act -- that Section reads in part as follows, Debts which have priority, \"The debts to have priority, in advance of the payment of dividends to creditors, and to be paid in full out of bankrupt estates, and the order of payment, shall be (1) the costs and expenses of administration, including the actual and necessary costs and expenses of preserving the estate subsequent to filing the petition.\"","start":267.757,"stop":296.125,"duration":28.37},{"text":"The term \"cost and expenses\" has never been defined by Congress and consequently, we argue that the term bears the meaning which had been required over the years in other insolvency proceedings, mainly equity receiverships.","start":296.125,"stop":316.611,"duration":20.49},{"text":"Claims for torts committed in equity receiverships by agents of the receiver have absolutely uniformly been held to be expenses of administration and to be entitled a priority.","start":316.611,"stop":329.716,"duration":13.11},{"text":"We've cited a large number of cases in our brief which of course, I'm not going to refer to but I would like to make one short -- read one short quotation by my -- decision by this Court, The Farmers' Loan and -- not but this Court -- sorry, it's a lower court case, the Farmers' Loan and Trust Company versus the Northern Pacific.","start":329.716,"stop":348.182,"duration":18.47},{"text":"Such claims for injuries occurring in the receiver's own management are paid.","start":348.182,"stop":352.792,"duration":4.61},{"text":"It is true.","start":352.792,"stop":354.121,"duration":1.33},{"text":"In preference to the mortgaged debt not for the reason of their preferential nature nor because of any superior equity in their favor over claims for damages which arose before the receiver was appointed.","start":354.121,"stop":367.717,"duration":13.6},{"text":"But because there are liabilities which were incurred by the receiver in the course of his own operation of the road and are payable by him as other expenses of management.","start":367.717,"stop":379.898,"duration":12.18},{"text":"Now, all of the text riders that we've been able to find, every single one without exception says that torts committed by a receiver in the operation of the business and I make no distinction between equity receiverships and bankruptcy receiverships, are expenses of administration.","start":379.898,"stop":398.795,"duration":18.9}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So you don't find any -- put any significance in the fact that this is Chapter XI rather than straight bankruptcy?","start":398.795,"stop":409.726,"duration":10.93}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, as such in --","start":409.726,"stop":411.139,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think the same result should occur if the trustee in bankrupt -- straight bankruptcy had taken possession of this building and then invert down --","start":411.139,"stop":417.907,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":417.907,"stop":418.229,"duration":0.32},{"text":"I did -- I think there's no question at all about it.","start":418.229,"stop":420.993,"duration":2.76},{"text":"I made no distinction at all as long as the tort is committed by an agent of the trustee or of the receiver --","start":420.993,"stop":428.024,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Although I suppose you would concede it's much clearer in the Chapter X than this would have?","start":428.024,"stop":432.395,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- the rules of equity apply, yes sir, I believe as opposed to Section 64.","start":432.395,"stop":438.368,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don't think the difference between the rule under Chapter X and the rule under XI which uses 64 is -- a difference in the context of this case?","start":438.368,"stop":448.294,"duration":9.93}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think it makes any difference in this case, sir, because I think it's quite clear under 64 that it should be paid, allows expenses of administration.","start":448.294,"stop":460.413,"duration":12.12},{"text":"Collier said so and it's interesting to me that the Government quotes Collier repeatedly as an authority but it does -- but in no place do they quote this action, it says that these are payable as expenses of administration.","start":460.413,"stop":474.375,"duration":13.96}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Does Collier really said -- say it on the facts somewhere to this case?","start":474.375,"stop":479.231,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it makes it -- the general statement, sir.","start":479.231,"stop":481.43,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What's your citation about it?","start":481.43,"stop":483.73,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, can you find that for me?","start":483.73,"stop":484.581,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's alright.","start":484.581,"stop":485.305,"duration":0.72},{"text":"It's in your brief and I have it.","start":485.305,"stop":486.576,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's in the brief, sir, yes.","start":486.576,"stop":489.054,"duration":2.48},{"text":"Well, we contend to any other result where -- would manifest, it'd be unjust.","start":489.054,"stop":493.764,"duration":4.71},{"text":"Chapter XI proceeding contemplates that the debtor will be rehabilitated and it is of course done for the benefit of the general creditors and of it's shareholders and we contend that it would be -- since it's being operated for their benefit, that to permit their receiver to engage in business which would benefit these general creditors and yet hold that they are immune from any liability for tort such as this would not only be unjust but would be unconstitutional.","start":493.764,"stop":531.802,"duration":38.04},{"text":"Apparently, everybody concedes that contractual liabilities entered into by the receiver are proper expenses and -- but the Government now argues that tort claims have no standing at all.","start":531.802,"stop":548.341,"duration":16.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Why would it be unconstitutional if the claimant of this kind was put to the bond of the receiver for good administration?","start":548.341,"stop":562.207,"duration":13.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Put to the bond, sir?","start":562.207,"stop":563.799,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, if they -- if there's a bond, they puts up a bond to guarantee against maladministration and why would it be unconstitutional if the claimants were left to that?","start":563.799,"stop":578.142,"duration":14.34}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I don't know the size of the bond but such is not --","start":578.142,"stop":583.579,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But I don't know either but what if things of these magnitude are to be charged against the whole estate so was to wipeout all of the legitimate claimants against the bankrupt, why would it be unconstitutional to leave the claimants for maladministration up to the bond that's put up for good administration?","start":583.579,"stop":613.28,"duration":29.7}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it's not equal protection of the laws, sir, as I see it.","start":613.28,"stop":617.212,"duration":3.93},{"text":"If it --","start":617.212,"stop":617.403,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it equal protection of the laws to give them all the money and leave the -- all the creditors out?","start":617.403,"stop":625.114,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I don't think the amount of the claim, if this claim amounted to $5,000 for example, we wouldn't be here.","start":625.114,"stop":632.471,"duration":7.36},{"text":"I don't think they would even have contested it but if --","start":632.471,"stop":635.957,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you take it all?","start":635.957,"stop":637.83,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, sir, it's because -- I say that if a tort claim is a cost or an expense by the administration and Congress has seen fit to give those expenses a number one priority that I don't believe that the nature of the claim can be determined or should be determined at least by the amount of the tort claims.","start":637.83,"stop":661.478,"duration":23.65},{"text":"I don't think that just because the -- receiver was so --","start":661.478,"stop":665.426,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's a statutory interpretation but I would ask you what the unconstitutionality of it would be if they are left only to the bond rather than to assets of the estate.","start":665.426,"stop":680.473,"duration":15.05},{"text":"You said it would be grossly unconstitutional and I'm just asking the question.","start":680.473,"stop":686.114,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I don't even know that a bond that goes to -- into this area isn't a bond, a fidelity bond.","start":686.114,"stop":693.18,"duration":7.07},{"text":"I am not a bankruptcy expert at all but as my understanding of the bond is primarily a fidelity bond there's a question of insurance as to whether he took out insurance or not.","start":693.18,"stop":703.659,"duration":10.48},{"text":"In fact, I don't know but obviously he did take out very much.","start":703.659,"stop":707.863,"duration":4.2},{"text":"But I don't think that we should be that that -- the question of whether the receiver did or didn't take out a sufficient bond or whether he was grossly negligent instead of slightly negligent should determine the issue of whether these are properly allowable expenses of administration in bankruptcy.","start":707.863,"stop":729.75,"duration":21.89}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I gather that if the building had burned the day before bankruptcy why -- your -- this would just been a general claim?","start":729.75,"stop":739.01,"duration":9.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean, the day before bankruptcy Your Honor or the day before the filing of a petition for --","start":739.01,"stop":742.484,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"A day before the arrangement --","start":742.484,"stop":745.292,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no doubt about that, sir, but there's --","start":745.292,"stop":746.971,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- but now could it -- you say if it burns the day after however, the day after the petitioners filed and a receiver has pointed that it does become an administration expense.","start":746.971,"stop":756.108,"duration":9.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If that's the receiver's faults, yes.","start":756.108,"stop":760.556,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But the receiver really has to change anything in the 24 hours, it's the same building, it's the same situation, why and what is the -- what has the adjoining owner's building has damaged to done -- to further the goals of the receivership?","start":760.556,"stop":781.686,"duration":21.13},{"text":"I grant you that most administration expenses are given priority for a given priority for reason.","start":781.686,"stop":788.747,"duration":7.06},{"text":"And what reason that normally underlies priority for administration expenses does indicate priority for this kind of a claim?","start":788.747,"stop":799.117,"duration":10.37}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor I perhaps ought to switch to the Nicholas case which was decided about a year and a half ago where this Court held that taxes imposed during the period while the receiver was in -- during the arrangement as well as penalties were properly under the Section 64a (1) expenses of administration whereas the taxes that had to do with the prearrangement period were not.","start":799.117,"stop":834.758,"duration":35.64}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, taxes represents service from -- represent payment for governmental services.","start":834.758,"stop":842.833,"duration":8.07}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, but the penalties done -- and I don't think that the -- I think the penalties are even more remote than a tort claim.","start":842.833,"stop":857.047,"duration":14.21},{"text":"I think that it's the accident, the thing that has given all of the ?","start":857.047,"stop":861.109,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But the penalties were supported by the taxes?","start":861.109,"stop":865.235,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the penalties are for failure to file in that case, for a failure to file returns.","start":865.235,"stop":870.783,"duration":5.55},{"text":"But I think the Nicholas case and as well as the Boteler case, upon which it was based, make it clear that there's an entirely different character to claims that arise against the receiver as such.","start":870.783,"stop":887.352,"duration":16.57},{"text":"The receiver is only liable in his representative capacity and it's the funds under his control that are to be charged with.","start":887.352,"stop":899.102,"duration":11.75},{"text":"He isn't liable personally and I think that the -- all I can say that the fact that happened during the receiver's administration has uniformly been and make it an entirely different category.","start":899.102,"stop":917.415,"duration":18.31},{"text":"I have some other cases, sir.","start":917.415,"stop":919.992,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"All tort claims stand on the same example in the -- all torts of receivers stand on exactly the same basis?","start":919.992,"stop":928.923,"duration":8.93}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor --","start":928.923,"stop":929.308,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Wouldn't distinct -- between one tort or another.","start":929.308,"stop":931.165,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I say you don't make any distinction between the claims of -- if Your Honor is referring to the Government's argument that business invitee would stand on a different category from somebody who just happen to own a house across the street.","start":931.165,"stop":946.351,"duration":15.19},{"text":"I say there isn't any difference.","start":946.351,"stop":948.67,"duration":2.32},{"text":"As a matter of fact, the Government has, of course, made some concessions in its brief which is contrary to what it made before.","start":948.67,"stop":959.629,"duration":10.96},{"text":"And it says that -- now, it says, been said at the lower courts but it now it says that a -- if the plaintiff was a business invitee, he would be entitled to share what the -- this would be a business expense.","start":959.629,"stop":980.369,"duration":20.74},{"text":"Well, whether you didn't realize here that there's some business invitees whose claims had been wiped out by this.","start":980.369,"stop":986.694,"duration":6.32},{"text":"But more fundamentally than not, I know of absolutely no authority whatever for the proposition that because a claimant, let us say, here was -- who had at least property on the second floor at the Fretz Building, let us say, the highest property destroyed.","start":986.694,"stop":1011.124,"duration":24.43},{"text":"As oppose to a plaintiff who own a house across the street which was burned up with all his possessions.","start":1011.124,"stop":1017.854,"duration":6.73},{"text":"That the tenant should be paid in full and the perfectly innocent property owner across the street gets nothing.","start":1017.854,"stop":1025.549,"duration":7.69},{"text":"I know no authority for sure.","start":1025.549,"stop":1027.185,"duration":1.64},{"text":"I don't see any justice --","start":1027.185,"stop":1028.779,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is this vital authority on this whole principle?","start":1028.779,"stop":1032.798,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, such authority if there is, however, I --","start":1032.798,"stop":1035.271,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- very little.","start":1035.271,"stop":1036.499,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the case of Vass against Conron Brothers which has been -- could he bitterly attack by my opponents, is good authority even if we say that its -- that it is dictum.","start":1036.499,"stop":1055.132,"duration":18.63},{"text":"I don't really believe that it is ictum but in Vass, the facts were these.","start":1055.132,"stop":1070.094,"duration":14.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind telling how this fire happened?","start":1070.094,"stop":1073.397,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How it happened, sir?","start":1073.397,"stop":1074.356,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1074.356,"stop":1074.814,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1074.814,"stop":1076.176,"duration":1.36},{"text":"There was an engineer who was working on some frozen sprinkler pipes.","start":1076.176,"stop":1082.058,"duration":5.88},{"text":"I think he was trying to drain the pipes so he could get the sprinkle system working again.","start":1082.058,"stop":1086.896,"duration":4.84},{"text":"And in the course of doing that, he -- it was so cold that night, he hooked up a heater to the -- I think it was the barbs that runs the elevator which had very high voltage.","start":1086.896,"stop":1097.317,"duration":10.42},{"text":"And of course, it had much more voltage for this heater then he must have gone away and after there, it caught fire and set fire to the building.","start":1097.317,"stop":1105.642,"duration":8.33},{"text":"And with no sprinkler system and with a high wind blowing, and it reached to a building.","start":1105.642,"stop":1110.898,"duration":5.26},{"text":"It just became an absolute holocaust and they couldn't get it out for hours and hours; and it just burned everything up in the neighborhood.","start":1110.898,"stop":1121.247,"duration":10.35}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose that really the question is whether the category of administrative expense ought to be narrowly construed to those things that are necessary to unable the business to continue to function during the period of the Bankruptcy Act proceeding.","start":1121.247,"stop":1146.21,"duration":24.96},{"text":"And I suppose you can -- you can fit most everything in there that has been covered by the cases including the payment of taxes.","start":1146.21,"stop":1158.582,"duration":12.37},{"text":"And on that theory, I suppose your adversary argues that the payment of a tort claim has nothing whatever to do with the purpose of that category, namely, to unable the business to keep operating during the Bankruptcy Act period.","start":1158.582,"stop":1179.061,"duration":20.48}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, it -- however, the business --","start":1179.061,"stop":1181.207,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not trying to suggest the magnitude on it.","start":1181.207,"stop":1183.705,"duration":2.5},{"text":"I think maybe to my mind up to this moment perhaps seems to be the issue.","start":1183.705,"stop":1190.602,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, however, the thing that I would like to emphasize is that the operation of the business is being done for the benefit of the I.J. Knight welding Company.","start":1190.602,"stop":1203.596,"duration":12.99},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, to take an example, suppose they discovered a goldmine in the ashes of this building so that I.J. Knight was worth 10 million dollars.","start":1203.596,"stop":1214.758,"duration":11.16},{"text":"We would not be entitled to a cent of it if this judgment is correct.","start":1214.758,"stop":1218.54,"duration":3.78},{"text":"Now, the statements had been made.","start":1218.54,"stop":1220.836,"duration":2.3},{"text":"We could have filed a claim on the 63a (7).","start":1220.836,"stop":1223.712,"duration":2.88},{"text":"That's not accurate.","start":1223.712,"stop":1225.946,"duration":2.23},{"text":"63a (7) by its terms is limited to claims against the bankrupt.","start":1225.946,"stop":1231.477,"duration":5.53},{"text":"This was not and never could be under our theory of the case, a claim against the bankrupt.","start":1231.477,"stop":1238.924,"duration":7.45},{"text":"And therefore, we could not have brought suit in the 63a (7).","start":1238.924,"stop":1242.763,"duration":3.84},{"text":"Now, this is being done for the benefit of the general creditors who'll be paid absolutely every penny if this judgment stands.","start":1242.763,"stop":1252.888,"duration":10.13},{"text":"I see no justice at all in letting them take away $378,000 more or less of cash when the business which is being operated for their benefit is destroyed by the negligence of their own representative.","start":1252.888,"stop":1269.463,"duration":16.58}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think I appreciate that but what you're doing then is to -- do you admit that that is the -- that what I have stated is the basis for the administrative priority category that is established idea?","start":1269.463,"stop":1287.041,"duration":17.58}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I don't really know what the exact basis of -- why the various priorities changed.","start":1287.041,"stop":1295.508,"duration":8.47},{"text":"I know that at one time, taxes for example, were put number one and later number four.","start":1295.508,"stop":1301.238,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but it is --","start":1301.238,"stop":1301.482,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And I don't -- I think in all honesty I would have to say.","start":1301.482,"stop":1306.121,"duration":4.64},{"text":"But I don't think that Congress had in mind the three and a half million dollar fire in an eight hundred thousand dollar estate when they talk about expenses that --","start":1306.121,"stop":1314.55,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me put it to you this way.","start":1314.55,"stop":1316.651,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Is there any authority for, including in the priority class, an item which is not conceptually related to the objective of continuing business during the Bankruptcy Act period?","start":1316.651,"stop":1336.372,"duration":19.72}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you say -- connected, the continuing business.","start":1336.372,"stop":1338.986,"duration":2.61},{"text":"This was connected to it.","start":1338.986,"stop":1340.514,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm asking if this -- the question.","start":1340.514,"stop":1343.51,"duration":3},{"text":"Do you know of any exception to that rule?","start":1343.51,"stop":1346.868,"duration":3.36}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know that Vass against Conron Brothers which I was about to refer to is a case in which the cold storage in a refrigerated plant, the plaintiff had been -- the Conron Brothers had been a tenant in the plant and when the property went into -- the bankruptcy was adjudicated, the trustee, Vass, confirmed the lease because he didn't try to throw him out.","start":1346.868,"stop":1389.075,"duration":42.21},{"text":"He continued on with it and there was an agreement that he would refrigerate the portion of the plant in which Conron Brothers had their property and he permitted that to breakdown.","start":1389.075,"stop":1402.062,"duration":12.99},{"text":"And the result was that Conron had some damages and it came up -- this is the 1932 case as I recall.","start":1402.062,"stop":1412.091,"duration":10.03},{"text":"They came up in a motion to enjoin the prosecution of the estate actions.","start":1412.091,"stop":1418.274,"duration":6.18},{"text":"But at the end of the decision, the -- Judge Hanft said, \"The liquidation of the lessee's resulting damages was as much a part of the usual administration in bankruptcy, as that of the pay of accountants, custodians or other assistants employed by the trustee.\"","start":1418.274,"stop":1439.536,"duration":21.26},{"text":"Now they object -- they attacked this decision on two grounds.","start":1439.536,"stop":1445.844,"duration":6.31},{"text":"One is that, in referring to the Supreme State Court.","start":1445.844,"stop":1452.077,"duration":6.23},{"text":"There were two counts.","start":1452.077,"stop":1453.044,"duration":0.97},{"text":"The first said that Vass booked the contract; the second said he was negligent.","start":1453.044,"stop":1459.159,"duration":6.12},{"text":"And on the second point, Judge Hand said, \"That has nothing.\"","start":1459.159,"stop":1463.41,"duration":4.25},{"text":"So they say, \"This isn't a tort case at all.","start":1463.41,"stop":1466.045,"duration":2.63},{"text":"This is a contract case.\"","start":1466.045,"stop":1468.374,"duration":2.33},{"text":"Now I say that what he was -- what Judge Hanft was saying is that as far as allowing this claim in -- bankruptcy court is concerned, it doesn't make any difference whether that liability is incurred because he broke the contract or because he did it negligently.","start":1468.374,"stop":1487.762,"duration":19.39},{"text":"Certainly, I don't think that if the suit had been brought, alleging simply negligence and not breach of contract, that there would have been any different result.","start":1487.762,"stop":1497.648,"duration":9.89},{"text":"Now, I think that this case -- they also savor for a second argument that this is dictum.","start":1497.648,"stop":1506.183,"duration":8.54},{"text":"It's a pretty cryptic opinion I would admit but I think that the only basis upon which Judge Hand could have put this end was that the must have been made that it would have been illegal and unconstitutional to have refused to give -- permit this man to pursue his suit.","start":1506.183,"stop":1526.457,"duration":20.27},{"text":"And therefore, he said, \"Well, it's alright to enjoin because we're going to allow it as an expense of administration.\"","start":1526.457,"stop":1534.013,"duration":7.56},{"text":"Now, does that -- I don't know if that answers Your Honor's question.","start":1534.013,"stop":1536.923,"duration":2.91},{"text":"There is one other case that's directly on point I think, In re (Inaudible) Company, which is a lower court decision in which there was a rigid patent claim which was allowed as an expense of administration.","start":1536.923,"stop":1554.718,"duration":17.8},{"text":"But they say that that was an unjust enrichment case which I didn't -- certainly, that was not the basis of the opinion.","start":1554.718,"stop":1560.757,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"One of the brief show that Learned Hand case as to whether that was argued or not.","start":1560.757,"stop":1567.04,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether that point was --","start":1567.04,"stop":1568.032,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1568.032,"stop":1569.207,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, on the same stand, I never went there before to read them.","start":1569.207,"stop":1575.494,"duration":6.29},{"text":"They --","start":1575.494,"stop":1576.432,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You said you thought it must be -- it must have been argued and I wondered what's your basis (Voice Overlap)?","start":1576.432,"stop":1580.968,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't -- there would've been no particular reason to put it in for that -- there hasn't been any basis or so it seems to me.","start":1580.968,"stop":1594.317,"duration":13.35},{"text":"Well, but both the trustee and the Government have tried to say that the tort claims, there's something tainted about a tort claim that just because it's based on negligence as opposed to a breach of contract or some other theory of the law that in order to be (Inaudible), I say to this Court that I think that the only reason, we have had the difficulty that we've had up to now is the amount of the claims.","start":1594.317,"stop":1628.491,"duration":34.17},{"text":"Just last year where Mr. Justice Douglas said that there's an overriding consideration that equitable principles governing the exercise of bankruptcy jurisdiction, that's the Bank of America against England case.","start":1628.491,"stop":1641.558,"duration":13.07},{"text":"And I submit to the court that equitable principles require that the -- that this be considered an expense of administration with the priority which Congress has given to it and that any other decision is a -- unjust and I submit, unconstitutional.","start":1641.558,"stop":1670.741,"duration":29.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why do you say (Inaudible) unconstitutional?","start":1670.741,"stop":1674.786,"duration":4.05},{"text":"I don't get you.","start":1674.786,"stop":1679.416,"duration":4.63},{"text":"I don't your unconstitutional claim?","start":1679.416,"stop":1682.388,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- Your Honor,","start":1682.388,"stop":1682.602,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand it --","start":1682.602,"stop":1684.118,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We would have no remedy.","start":1684.118,"stop":1686.787,"duration":2.67},{"text":"The effect of this decision is to say that we have no remedy at all because we can't go after the receiver personally.","start":1686.787,"stop":1695.725,"duration":8.94},{"text":"We can't go after the bankrupt.","start":1695.725,"stop":1699.99,"duration":4.27},{"text":"There is no proceeding anywhere.","start":1699.99,"stop":1702.495,"duration":2.5},{"text":"There is no provision in this Bankruptcy Act anywhere where the payment of a claim against the receiver except under expenses in administrations in 64a (1).","start":1702.495,"stop":1715.053,"duration":12.56},{"text":"I'm talking now about a tort of a receiver.","start":1715.053,"stop":1718.589,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government does disagree with you on that (Voice Overlap)?","start":1718.589,"stop":1720.939,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They say -- they say -- Your Honor, they said that we had a -- we had a claim under 63a (7) but may I point out that the preamble of 63 says, \"Debts of the bankrupt may be proved and allowed against his estate which are founded upon a certain number of things, number 7, which is this tort.\"","start":1720.939,"stop":1742.552,"duration":21.61},{"text":"Now this is as I have said to you, Your Honor, this was not and could not be a debt of the bankrupt.","start":1742.552,"stop":1750.045,"duration":7.49},{"text":"This was a debt which was incurred by the receiver only.","start":1750.045,"stop":1755.998,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it's going to be held that -- on what your other -- the other side claim.","start":1755.998,"stop":1762.273,"duration":6.27},{"text":"I suppose the Court --","start":1762.273,"stop":1763.4,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, Section --","start":1763.4,"stop":1764.117,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) make statutory to make your share under the state in some week, doesn't it?","start":1764.117,"stop":1769.675,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"As a general creditor under 63a (7).","start":1769.675,"stop":1771.417,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1771.417,"stop":1772.978,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But Your Honor, we can't see us a general creditor.","start":1772.978,"stop":1777.286,"duration":4.31},{"text":"Section 63 will not permit anybody who doesn't have a claim against the bankrupt to file a general claim.","start":1777.286,"stop":1785.858,"duration":8.57},{"text":"We have now a general claim.","start":1785.858,"stop":1787.156,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But this is a claim either against the bankrupt or against the receiver.","start":1787.156,"stop":1791.868,"duration":4.71},{"text":"I would suppose and agree with the whole that it's not against the receiver.","start":1791.868,"stop":1797.912,"duration":6.04},{"text":"I don't suppose we (Inaudible) from saying its against the bankrupt.","start":1797.912,"stop":1801.162,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It can't be, Your Honor.","start":1801.162,"stop":1804.064,"duration":2.9},{"text":"Section 63a (7), as I just read.","start":1804.064,"stop":1806.768,"duration":2.7},{"text":"It says, \"Debts of the bankrupt may be proved.\"","start":1806.768,"stop":1811.085,"duration":4.32},{"text":"And this -- the bankrupt had been out of control of this building for six weeks.","start":1811.085,"stop":1818.552,"duration":7.47},{"text":"Now, I'd like to point one other thing out where --","start":1818.552,"stop":1820.672,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Bankrupt's property to the extent that he hasn't any interest in it of any kind or (Inaudible).","start":1820.672,"stop":1828.086,"duration":7.41}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it's entirely possible that as much as a hundred thousand dollars and more may be returned to the bankrupt.","start":1828.086,"stop":1835.602,"duration":7.52},{"text":"But if this decision stands, we won't get a penny of it.","start":1835.602,"stop":1839.079,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that's the reason -- the main reason for that is that you didn't file a lawsuit, isn't it?","start":1839.079,"stop":1847.049,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, a lawsuit cannot automatically be proven.","start":1847.049,"stop":1854.55,"duration":7.5},{"text":"Your Honor is talking about a common lawsuit?","start":1854.55,"stop":1856.601,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1856.601,"stop":1857.766,"duration":1.16},{"text":"Which is under 63a (7) --","start":1857.766,"stop":1857.845,"duration":0.08},{"text":"A common law action --","start":1857.845,"stop":1859.235,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it has to be --","start":1859.235,"stop":1859.513,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"A common law action only establishes that the amount of the damages and that there was a claim against the bankrupt but it may not be proved.","start":1859.513,"stop":1872.3,"duration":12.79},{"text":"The -- even the judgment may not be proved unless the claim which gave rise to the cause of action is itself provable.","start":1872.3,"stop":1882.169,"duration":9.87},{"text":"Now I say here, that we couldn't have sued the bankrupt.","start":1882.169,"stop":1886.397,"duration":4.23},{"text":"We could only have sued the receiver.","start":1886.397,"stop":1888.793,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Now, if we -- suing the receiver does not get us anywhere unless we can prove it as either as a preferred claim or as a general claim.","start":1888.793,"stop":1899.056,"duration":10.26},{"text":"Now, as I say, it can't be a general claim, Mr. Justice Black.","start":1899.056,"stop":1902.143,"duration":3.09},{"text":"It's just -- the Bankruptcy Act doesn't permit it and the only place --","start":1902.143,"stop":1905.66,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But what if it's a --","start":1905.66,"stop":1906.864,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where a claim of this sort against the receiver can be proved, it is 64a (1); there's no other place.","start":1906.864,"stop":1913.913,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What if it has been a debtor, it have possession instead of a receiver under Chapter XI?","start":1913.913,"stop":1917.752,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If whether -- there is no difference on my judgment sir.","start":1917.752,"stop":1921.492,"duration":3.74},{"text":"However, I think that we might have gone after the debtor in view of the fact that he is the tort misfeasance.","start":1921.492,"stop":1927.03,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Well, I don't know.","start":1927.03,"stop":1928.051,"duration":1.02},{"text":"That's -- it's a nice question.","start":1928.051,"stop":1930.219,"duration":2.17},{"text":"The -- this Court has said that a receiver as such is only liable in his representative capacity and that his actions -- in McNulta versus Lochridge, actions against the receiver or in law, actions against the receivership for the funds in the hands of the receiver.","start":1930.219,"stop":1953.006,"duration":22.79},{"text":"And its contracts, misfeasances, negligence and liabilities are official and not personal and judgments against him as receiver are payable only from the funds in his hands.","start":1953.006,"stop":1966.482,"duration":13.48},{"text":"Now, 28 U.S.C.Section 959 it says that, \"A receiver shall operate a business -- that is a receiver in a case before the federal court, -- shall operate the business as though he were person or corporation running a business.\"","start":1966.482,"stop":1990.763,"duration":24.28},{"text":"And if this decision is allowed to stand, this means that they can act as they like.","start":1990.763,"stop":1999.831,"duration":9.07},{"text":"He can be just as negligent.","start":1999.831,"stop":2001.537,"duration":1.71},{"text":"And if -- of course, it's admitted for the purpose of this argument that there's no question about the negligence of the --","start":2001.537,"stop":2009.433,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's possible -- it's possible that --","start":2009.433,"stop":2011.991,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"His own personal liability issue?","start":2011.991,"stop":2014.201,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your -- this Court has held that they -- as in McNulta versus Lochridge that I've just read said, \"Such claims for injuries occurring on the receivers own management or -- no, I'm sorry.\"","start":2014.201,"stop":2034.755,"duration":20.55},{"text":"\"Actions against the receiver or no actions against the receivership or the funds in the hands of the receiver and his contracts, misfeasances, negligences and liabilities are official and not personal, and judgment against him as receiver are payable only from the funds in his hand.\"","start":2034.755,"stop":2050.58,"duration":15.82},{"text":"This is what this Court has held.","start":2050.58,"stop":2052.79,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2052.79,"stop":2062.112,"duration":9.32}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case, sir?","start":2062.112,"stop":2064.806,"duration":2.69},{"text":"No, I don't read the lower court same --","start":2064.806,"stop":2068.469,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2068.469,"stop":2073.996,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- is nothing.","start":2073.996,"stop":2075.748,"duration":1.75},{"text":"The Court --","start":2075.748,"stop":2076.061,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) it is payable, payable by the funds in his hand.","start":2076.061,"stop":2080.132,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It --","start":2080.132,"stop":2081.223,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2081.223,"stop":2083.696,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2083.696,"stop":2084.775,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It was nothing -- had nothing, it's a claim that survives bankruptcy.","start":2084.775,"stop":2088.741,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2088.741,"stop":2089.944,"duration":1.2},{"text":"No claim survives bankruptcy.","start":2089.944,"stop":2091.914,"duration":1.97},{"text":"That isn't a claim against the bankrupt.","start":2091.914,"stop":2094.431,"duration":2.52},{"text":"It has to be a claim against the bankrupt to survive bankruptcy.","start":2094.431,"stop":2099.253,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes, you've -- so you say it's not a (Inaudible) --","start":2099.253,"stop":2101.368,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We are and that is -- this is -- we just don't have any remedy after all under this decision and it doesn't make any difference.","start":2101.368,"stop":2110.66,"duration":9.29},{"text":"How much money is in this fund?","start":2110.66,"stop":2113.803,"duration":3.14},{"text":"What's it -- unless the receiver is personally liable but -- well, if Your Honor is going to change -- overrule this case, perhaps.","start":2113.803,"stop":2120.821,"duration":7.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be overruling (Inaudible) from the funds in his hand and the rule was that kind of a claim if payable (Inaudible).","start":2120.821,"stop":2133.492,"duration":12.67}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they said it's not -- it's not his personal responsibility.","start":2133.492,"stop":2137.122,"duration":3.63},{"text":"That's what this Court held.","start":2137.122,"stop":2139.819,"duration":2.7},{"text":"I say to the court that under this decision, we have no place to go; that these three-and-a-half million dollars in claims are -- going to get not one penny for my source--","start":2139.819,"stop":2150.084,"duration":10.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did they ever had -- there might have been insurance to cover this (Inaudible).","start":2150.084,"stop":2154.904,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there might have been, sir.","start":2154.904,"stop":2156.453,"duration":1.55},{"text":"I honestly don't know the answer to that.","start":2156.453,"stop":2158.26,"duration":1.81},{"text":"We have --","start":2158.26,"stop":2159.291,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If the receiver paid over -- to keep the building insured when he should have, I suppose his chargeable, he is sure chargeable, isn't it?","start":2159.291,"stop":2168.848,"duration":9.56}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Raeburn White, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think that he has three-and-a-half million dollars sir.","start":2168.848,"stop":2176.481,"duration":7.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess.","start":2176.481,"stop":2179.319,"duration":2.84}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Mar  4 - 5, 1968","petitioner":"Reading Company","respondent":"Brown","docket":"127","citation":"391 US 471 (1968)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/391/471","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 3, 1968"}